revision.text:
'''David B. Wexler''' is a Professor of Law at the [[University of Puerto Rico]] in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], a Distinguished Research Professor of Law Emeritus  at the [[James E. Rogers College of Law]], [[Tucson, Arizona]], and an Honorary President of the  International Society for Therapeutic Jurisprudence.

Wexler is credited with first discussing the [[therapeutic jurisprudence]] perspective in 1987,<ref name="Association2001">{{cite book|author=American Bar Association|title=ABA Journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vgAp__wf5C4C&pg=PA79|accessdate=25 September 2012|date=May 2001|publisher=American Bar Association|pages=79–|issn=0747-0088}}- ''</ref><ref>''The Development of Therapeutic Jurisprudence: From Theory to Practice''.  David Wexler . 68 Revista Juridica Universidad de Puerto Rico 691 (1999).</ref> and along with [[Bruce Winick]] is recognized as one of the two "leading scholars in this field."<ref name="Nolan2011">{{cite book|author=James L. Nolan|title=Legal Accents, Legal Borrowing: The International Problem-Solving Court Movement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jaPFYWjsoZEC&pg=PA88|accessdate=25 September 2012|date=21 April 2011|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-15014-7|pages=88–}}</ref>  He is a consultant on therapeutic jurisprudence to the [[National Judicial Institute of Canada]], and has served as a Fulbright Senior Specialist.  One author characterizes Wexler's jurisprudence as [[Radical center (politics)|radical cenrist]] in orientation.<ref>Satin, Mark (2004).  ''Radical Middle: The Politics We Need Now''.  Westview Press and Basic Books, p. 55.  {{ISBN|978-0-8133-4190-3}}.</ref> Constance Backhouse, a leading legal historian from Canada, has published a biography of Wexler and his work.<ref>Constance B. Backhouse, An Introduction to David Wexler, the Person Behind Therapeutic Jurisprudence, 2016, http://ssrn.com/abstract=2747488</ref>

== Published works ==
* ''Rehabilitating Lawyers: Principles of Therapeutic Jurisprudence for Criminal Law Practice'' ([[Carolina Academic Press]] 2008)  
*  ''Judging in a Therapeutic Key: Therapeutic Jurisprudence and the Courts'' (with [[Bruce Winick]]) (Carolina Academic Press 2003)
* ''Practicing Therapeutic Jurisprudence: Law as a Helping Profession'' (with Dennis P. Stolle and [[Bruce Winick]]) (Carolina Academic Press 2000)
* ''Law in a Therapeutic Key: Developments in Therapeutic Jurisprudence'' (with [[Bruce Winick]]) (Carolina Academic Press 1996)
* ''Essays in Therapeutic Jurisprudence'' (with [[Bruce Winick]]) (Carolina Academic Press 1991)
* ''Therapeutic Jurisprudence: The Law as a Therapeutic Agent'' (Carolina Academic Press 1990)
* ''Mental Health Law: Major Issues'' (Plenum Press 1981).

