'''EdSurge Inc.''' is an [[educational technology]] company that publishes newsletters and operates databases used by [[venture capital]]ists, teachers, school administrators and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconbeat.com/2012/08/29/edsurge-surges-ahead-with-new-funding |title=EdSurge Surges Ahead With New Funding – San Jose Mercury News |date=2012-08-29|accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref> In May 2018, EdSurge was identified by the [[Brookings Institution]] as one of the world's 16 leading "innovation spotters" in education. These organizations "are searching the globe to find, highlight, and sometimes support education innovations," Brookings wrote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/education-plus-development/2018/05/17/education-innovations-are-taking-root-around-the-world-what-do-they-have-in-common/|title=Education  innovations are taking root around the world; What do they have in common?|date=2018-05-17|accessdate=2018-05-27}}</ref>

EdSurge was founded in 2011 by [[Elizabeth Corcoran]], a former executive editor of [[Forbes]] and a former technology reporter for [[The Washington Post]], by Nick Punt, a former vice president at [[Inigral]], a private social network for higher education, by [[Matt Bowman]], a former Catholic school teacher, and by [[Agustin Vilaseca]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/08/29/edsurge-funding | work=Tech Crunch | title= EdSurge Nabs $400K From Washington Post, New Schools To Be A Resource For All Things EdTech |date=2012-08-29|accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref> 

As of December 2015, the company had raised $5.6 million in funding from investors including [[GSV Capital]], [[NewSchools Venture Fund]], Reach Capital, Catamount Ventures, 1776.vc, the [[Omidyar Network]], the Women's Venture Capital Fund, [[LearnCapital]]. and many angels.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Edtech company EdSurge scores $2.8 mln - PE HUB|url = https://www.pehub.com/2015/12/edtech-company-edsurge-scores-2-8-mln/|website = PE HUB|accessdate = 2015-12-15|language = en-US}}</ref> EdSurge’s initial funding in 2012 was led by [[The Washington Post Company]] and NewSchools Venture Fund, along with angel investors including [[Allen & Company]]’s Nancy Peretsman and Silicon Valley entrepreneur [[Judith Estrin]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://allthingsd.com/20120829/washington-post-invests-in-education-tech-site | work=All Things D |title=Washington Post Invests in Education Tech Site |date=2012-08-29|accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref>

EdSurge's commentary regularly appears in media outlets such as ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.fastcompany.com/1791482/newest-companies-coming-out-incubators-edtech | work=Fast Company | title= The New Companies Coming Out of Incubators: Ed Tech |date=2011-10-28|accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref> EdSurge's managing editor, Tony Wan, was named in 2014 to Forbes magazine's "30 Under 30" list, and EdSurge's senior editor, Mary Jo Madda, was named to the 2016 Forbes list, which highlights top achievers under age 30.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/special-report/2014/30-under-30/education.html | work=Forbes |title=30 Under 30 |date=2014-01-15|accessdate=2014-06-24}}</ref>[https://www.forbes.com/pictures/lmh45mmmd/mary-jo-madda-29/]

